    {
      "id": "8add3570da4fecfe4058b38d534f434b5e63ffca",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-02-03 07:58:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nThe RCU part looks good.\n\nDo we really have to use radix tree to manage user id on just one client node? Maybe lockless linked list would be enough, imo.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "3444b503936f360d61642e0bf4a15bd525bd0f90",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 7,
        "name": "Johann Lombardi",
        "email": "johann.lombardi@intel.com",
        "username": "johann",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-02-03 12:31:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nSo CLIO could use one radix tree per OSC *object* and quota isn't allow to use 2 radix trees per OSC *device* ? :)\nMore seriously, for system having many users (e.g. an university), this list can be quite big on a login/head node, so i would rather avoid scanning a list. While a radix tree can be seen as overkill, the overhead is very small (even null if quota is disabled) if we don't have many entries.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "02ebbfc9bb6762f60a9020b9185f95b436b5029e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 7,
        "name": "Johann Lombardi",
        "email": "johann.lombardi@intel.com",
        "username": "johann",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2012-02-03 15:17:35.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 4.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "aecee858a399dc5be86bd8352777f1c00fff6d5d",
      "author": {
